  "doc_id": "18336",
  "text": "Only 13 cases of tyrosinaemia type III have been described and the full clinical spectrum of this disorder is unknown [CITATION_1] . Many of the patients have presented with neurological symptoms including intellectual impairment, ataxia, increased tendon reflexes, tremors, microcephaly and seizures; some have been detected by the finding of a high tyrosine concentration on neonatal screening. The most common long-term complication has been intellectual impairment, found in 75% of the reported cases. None of the described cases have developed signs of liver disease in the long-term. Eye and skin lesions have not been reported so far, but as oculocutaneous symptoms are known to occur in association with hypertyrosinaemia it is reasonable to be aware of this possibility.",
